<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-591-508  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 591 508.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  June 25 1990 v7 n25 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lighter side. (DEC contract)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vizard, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     ContractsComputer IndustryCourtsFinancial Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>LIGHTER SIDEandM;It looks like DEC technology is once again on its way to court--this time,however, under more desirable circumstances all around.andM;DEC last week announced that the office of the chief administrative justicefor the Massachusetts Trial Courts is installing a financial managementsystem based on software from Interactive Systems of Lowell, Mass., runningon two VAX 6410 systems networked to 50 PCs.andM;Next year the financial software system, which provides fund accounting andreal-time budgetary control, will be extended across all nine departments ofthe Massachusetts Trial Courts.andP;  A total of 110 court offices will haveaccess to the system when the project is completed.andM;Given the problems with Massachusetts' state budget and the excessivecaseload of the state's trial system, it's reassuring to see Massachusettstaking a proactive stand on both issues.andM;Considering all the business that DEC's patent attorneys have given the courtsystems over the years, it's nice to see a little business coming DEC's wayas well.andO;</TEXT></DOC>